NFS284H1-F-20209.courseDescription: An introductory course to provide the fundamentals of human nutrition to enable students to understand and think critically about the complex interrelationships between food, nutrition, health and the environment.

NFS284H1-S-20209.courseDescription: An introductory course to provide the fundamentals of human nutrition to enable students to understand and think critically about the complex interrelationships between food, nutrition, health and the environment.
NFS284H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online; learning is self-paced and is not reliant on a meeting schedule. There will be a scheduled test during the final assessment period.

NFS301H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Nutrition Literacy: Sorting Science from Snake Oil
NFS301H1-F-20209.courseDescription: This course will help students learn how to recognize the strengths and limitations of various nutrition research methods, find reliable nutrition information on the Internet and develop systematic thinking skills to critically evaluate the quality of nutrition information in both the scientific literature and popular media.

NFS302H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course will give an overview of the emerging and advancing role of chronic diet and supplements in athletics, performance and behavior.
NFS302H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online; learning is self-paced and is not reliant on a meeting schedule. There will be a scheduled test during the final assessment period.

NFS382H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Vitamin and Mineral Metabolism Throughout the Life Cycle
NFS382H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Micronutrients are essential for health throughout the life cycle. This course examines the role of micronutrients during development and ageing with some emphasis on disease prevention and pathogenesis. Students develop critical appraisal skills, an understanding of the principles of study design and learn to write in a scientific style.
NFS382H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.

NFS386H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Structure, composition and chemical and biochemical reactions in foods during postharvest/postmortem, processing, storage and utilisation. Implications for organoleptic properties, nutritional value, toxicity and human health.
NFS386H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online; learning is self paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. There will be a scheduled test during the final assessment period.

NFS394Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Research experience under the supervision of a Departmental staff member. The course entails designing and carrying out a small research project and the preparation and presentation of both a research proposal and a final report. Note that the research project NFS394Y1 requires the prior consent of a staff member who will supervise the project and departmental approval before enrolment. The student is responsible for locating a supervisor. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
NFS394Y1-Y-20209.prerequisite: NFS284H1, Permission of Department and Project Supervisor
NFS394Y1-Y-20209.webTimetableInstructions: For NFS394Y1: obtain applications from department website. Students must have located a supervisor for the project and obtained written permission of the department. Contact Dr. Mary L'Abbe: mary.labbe@utoronto.ca

NFS400H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Functional Foods and Nutraceuticals in Human Nutrition
NFS400H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course will demonstrate the rationale, including health benefits, development and marketing of functional foods and nutraceuticals.
NFS400H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions:
Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule. 

Lectures will be recorded to assist students, however group work is a major component of the course, and students must be in attendance during the course’s scheduled hours to meet with group members and the instructor and to participate in the group presentation.

NFS484H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Physiological and biochemical features of nutrient needs. The roles of nutrients in the development and adaptability of the whole body, organs and cells. Interpretation of current research data.
NFS484H1-F-20209.prerequisite: BCH210H1, CSB349H1/PSL350H1/BCH311H1, NFS284H1, (PSL300H1, PSL301H1)/PSL302Y1, (STA220H1, STA221H1/JBS229H1) or permission of instructor

NFS485H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Provides an integrated approach to how prokaryotes modulate nutrient availability and how they interact with the host to impact human health from a molecular perspective.
NFS485H1-F-20209.prerequisite: BCH210H1, CSB349H1/PSL350H1/BCH311H1/MGY311Y1, NFS284H1, (PSL300H1, PSL301H1)/PSL302Y1 or permission of the instructor

NFS486H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Obesity and its co-morbidities illustrated with pathophysiological and biochemical principles and clinical case studies.
NFS486H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.

NFS487H1-F-20209.courseDescription: The impact of the human genome on nutrition research. Experimental approaches to investigating gene-diet interactions. Understanding how genetic variability affects nutrient response, and how dietary factors regulate gene expression. Application of the various ‘omics’ technologies to nutrition research as well as exploring the social, legal and ethical issues associated with direct-to-consumer marketing of genetic tests for personalized nutrition.

NFS488H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Occurrence, mechanism of action, safety and health implications of chemicals naturally present in or added to foods. Interactions of nutrients and toxicants and the effects on their metabolism and utilization. Food safety evaluation and regulatory control.
NFS488H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.

NFS489H1-F-20209.courseDescription: This course provides an integrated approach to how brain function regulates and in turn is regulated by nutrition from a biochemical perspective.

NFS490H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course focuses on current issues in international and community nutrition including global and domestic food security, micronutrient deficiencies and other forms of undernutrition, maternal and infant/child nutrition, dietary guidance, and food and nutrition policy. The course will consider the environmental, sociopolitical, cultural and biosocial contexts of nutrition.
NFS490H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.

NFS494Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Research experience under the supervision of a Departmental staff member. The course entails designing and carrying out a small research project and the preparation and presentation of both a research proposal and a final report. Note that the research project NFS494Y1 requires the prior consent of a staff member who will supervise the project and departmental approval before enrolment. The student is responsible for locating a supervisor. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
NFS494Y1-Y-20209.prerequisite: NFS284H1, Permission of Department and Project Supervisor
